<span id="freeTextContainer5977182693069402518">In my opinion, this is the Christmas book. Forget <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/5326.A_Christmas_Carol' title='A Christmas Carol by Charles Dickens' rel='nofollow noopener'>A Christmas Carol</a> or anything else resembling wholesome Christmas stories, Skipping Christmas is a destined classic. What can I say, the concept of skipping Christmas entirely and going on a cruise instead just speaks to my Grinch-y soul.<br/><br/><img src='https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1483118634ra/21580784.gif' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/>This year I opted to re-read the audiobook version which is narrated by Dennis Boutsikaris who portrays Luther Krank perfectly in all his deadpan humorous glory. When I first discovered this novel, many, many yea</span>
  <span id="freeText5977182693069402518" style="display:none">In my opinion, this is the Christmas book. Forget <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/5326.A_Christmas_Carol" title="A Christmas Carol by Charles Dickens" rel="nofollow noopener">A Christmas Carol</a> or anything else resembling wholesome Christmas stories, Skipping Christmas is a destined classic. What can I say, the concept of skipping Christmas entirely and going on a cruise instead just speaks to my Grinch-y soul.<br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1483118634ra/21580784.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>This year I opted to re-read the audiobook version which is narrated by Dennis Boutsikaris who portrays Luther Krank perfectly in all his deadpan humorous glory. When I first discovered this novel, many, many years ago… I almost glanced over it because “John Grisham? Isn’t that the guy that writes legal thrillers?” Yep, he sure is, but apparently he also has a humorous side. Many of you have likely seen the film adaptation <a href="http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0388419/" rel="nofollow noopener">Christmas with the Kranks</a> which is all sorts of hilarious (especially with the book lacking that sidesplitting scene after Luther gets botox), but this short novel is an amusing way to spend a few hours surrounded by Christmas cheer as you contemplate an alternative to it all.</span>
